Hello, 

I'm **dynamically creating components** in angular. I'm working with [Wavemaker](https://www.wavemaker.com/custom-studio/) on a Web App. In the preview, it is working just fine, but the deployed App returns this error.


```
var dynamicServicePerson = App.getDependency('DynamicComponentService');

function getTabsPersonAcc(acc) {
        gcp = [];
        for (var t = 0; t < acc.length; t++) {
            gcp.push("<wm-tabpane name='tabpane1000_" + c + "' title='" + acc[t] + "' backgroundcolor='#EFF3F6'>" +
                "<wm-layoutgrid name='layoutgrid1000_" + c + "'>" +
                "<wm-gridrow name='gridrow1000_" + c + "'>" +
                "<wm-gridcolumn columnwidth='12' name='gridcolumn1000_" + c + "'padding='1em' horizontalalign='center'>" +
                "<wm-tile name='tile1000_" + c + "'class='note' margin='unset unset 1em unset'>" +
                "<wm-prefab prefabname='D3_Area_Chart' name='D3_Area_Chart1" + c + "' account='" + acc[t] + "' url='https://api.myjson.com/bins/jxn53'></wm-prefab>'" +
                "</wm-tile>" + "</wm-gridcolumn>" + "</wm-gridrow>" + "</wm-layoutgrid>" + "</wm-tabpane>");
            c++;
        }
        getTabsPersonEntity(gcp);
        c = 0;
    }

function getData(num) {
 try {
            const pr = getPerson(num);
            pr.then(function(result) {
                if (result !== undefined && result.length > 0) {
                    const wait = async() => {
                        const person = await (result);
                        getTabsPersonAcc(person);
                    }
                    wait();
                } else {
                    getTabsPersonEntityNoAcc();
                }
            })
        } catch (e) {
            if (e instanceof ReferenceError) {
                console.log(e, true);
            } else {
                console.log(e, false);
            }
        }
    }

function complete() {
        setTimeout(function() {
            var plgP = "<wm-layoutgrid name='layoutgrid4000_" + b + "'><wm-gridrow name='gridrow4000_" + b + "'>" +
                "<wm-gridcolumn columnwidth='12' name='gridcolumn4000_" + b + "'padding='1em'>" +
                "<wm-tabs name='tabs4000" + b + "' transition='slide'>" + tpp + "</wm-tabs></wm-gridcolumn></wm-gridrow></wm-layoutgrid>";
            try {
                dynamicServicePerson.addComponent($('[name="gridPersonEntity"]')[0], plgP, Page);
            } catch (e) {
                if (e instanceof ReferenceError) {
                    console.log(e, true);
                } else {
                    console.log(e, false);
                }
            }
        }, 4000);
    }

function getTabpaneEntity() {
        for (var i = 1; i <= data.length; i++) {
            try {
                var num = data[b].id;
                getData(num);
                b++;
            } catch (e) {
                if (e instanceof ReferenceError) {
                    console.log(e, true);
                } else {
                    console.log(e, false);
                }
            }
        }
        complete();
    }
    getTabpaneEntity();
```

The function checks for data in the database and returns the names of each row in the DB in an HTML tab-pane. 

I'm pretty new to programming, so maybe the code is a bit rough.

Thanks

Reference link 
[https://stackoverflow.com/questions/57668742/is-it-possible-to-show-remain-time-or-percentage-on-module-lazy-loading-module](url)

I want to show loading times or percentages when lazy loading modules. I want to show the time it took to load the module in real time.

I have tried the RouteConfigLoadStart and RouteConfigLoadEnd methods and they work fine. When loading, the module loader component displays and when done the component switches off, but I want to show how much time is remaining to load the module.

Component.ts:

this.router.events.subscribe(event => {
  if (event instanceof RouteConfigLoadStart || event instanceof ResolveStart) {
    this.moduleLoading = true;
  }
  if (event instanceof RouteConfigLoadEnd || event instanceof ResolveEnd) {
    this.moduleLoading = false;
  }
});
component.html:

<div class="content-wrapper" style="padding: 0px;">
  <div *ngIf="moduleLoading" class="square-box-loader" style="left: 56%;">
    <div class="square-box-loader-container">
      <div class="square-box-loader-corner-top"></div>
      <div class="square-box-loader-corner-bottom"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="square-box-loader-square"></div>
  </div>
  <router-outlet *ngIf="!moduleLoading"></router-outlet>
</div>
I want to show the remaining time to load the modules. For example, 5 seconds remaining or 10% loaded / 50% loaded, etc.

How would I go about showing percentages loaded or amount of time until loading is complete?

`addComponentLogic` was showing quite high on the expanding rows benchmarks profile and it turned out that it does unnecessary memory read / writes:
- native host node was read twice (` getNativeByTNode(hostTNode, lView)` and `lView[hostTNode.index]`);
- `componentView[T_HOST]` was set twice (once in `createLView` and second time explicitly).

# üêû bug report

### Affected Package
@angular/core


### Is this a regression?

_


### Description

I have object:
```typescript
  public model = {
    field: "blabal",
    field2: [1,2]
  };
```
and use it like this:
```html
<app-component-2 
        [model] = "(model$ | async)?.field2"
>
</app-component-2>
```
where `model$`:

```typescript
 public model$ = new Subject();

  onClick() {
    this.model$.next({...this.model})
  }
```

in `app-component-2` I have `ngOnChanges`:
```typescript
 ngOnChanges(changes){
    this.i++;
    console.log(changes.model.currentValue === changes.model.previousValue);
  }
``` 

`ngOnChanges` have been called each time when i call `onClick` function. But I don't change  array `field2`.

## üî¨ Minimal Reproduction

https://stackblitz.com/edit/angular-m7zzct

1) Click on "Just create new object only for model"
ER:  ngOnChanges shouldn't be called
AR: ngOnChanges have been called


